Data Cleaning and Preprocessing Functions¶

Binary Decision Mapping Function¶

In [ ]:
#This function will be used later to re-map battery decision
good = ['GOOD BATTERY','GOOD RECHARGE']
bad = ['REPLACE BATTERY','BADCELL SHORT REPLACE']

def batterydecision(status):
    if status in good:
        return 'GOOD BATTERY'
    elif status in bad:
        return 'BAD BATTERY'
    else:
        return status

           33: 'REST & RETEST',
           126: 'NO DECISION',
           255: 'No Decision'}

Outlier Removal Function¶

In [ ]:
#Function for outlier removal will be used later in the code 

def remove_outliers(df):
    # Selecting data that Voltage less than 30V
    df = df.loc[df['Voltage'] < 16]

    # df = df.loc[df['Voltage'] >= 11.4]

    # Selecting data that average equal or less than 18
    df = df.loc[df['Average'] <= 18]

    # Selecting data that min equal or less than 12
    df = df.loc[df['Min'] <= 12]

    # Selecting data that max equal or less than 16
    df = df.loc[df['Max'] <= 16]

    # Selecting data that bounce back equal or less than 16
    df = df.loc[df['Bounce_Back'] <= 16]

    # Selecting data that slope bounce back from the range [-.5;.5]
    df = df.loc[(df['Slope_Bounce_Back'] <= 0.5) & (df['Slope_Bounce_Back'] >= 0.005)]

    # Selecting data that slope drop from the range [-2;2]
    df = df.loc[(df['Slope_Drop'] <= 2) & (df['Slope_Drop'] >= -2)]

    return df

Feature Egineering Function¶

In [ ]:
#This function calculates conductance and adds column to dataframe. Then it updates the column names, and sets the datatype each feature
def clean_data(df):

    #Add Conductance column 
    df['Conductance'] = df.Measured/df.Rated

    # Rename columns using the provided column_names list
    df = df.rename(columns=dict(zip(df.columns, column_names)))
    
    # Reorder the DataFrame using the desired column order
    df = df[['Test_Record_Detail_Id', 'Voltage', 'Rated', 'Measured','Conductance',
                'Battery_Decision', 'Min', 'Max', 'Standard_Deviation', 'Average',
                'Median', 'Bounce_Back', 'Drop', 'Slope_Bounce_Back', 'Slope_Drop',
                'Min_Volt_Below_19', 'Max_Volt_19_Above']]
    

    #Downcasting: Downcasting is the prcess of casting values to datatypes with lower byes. Somtimes the extra bytes are not used
    #and end up using more memory than needed. Downcasting can lower the size of dataframes, and help speed up processes later on. 

    df[['Voltage','Min','Max','Median','Bounce_Back','Drop','Min_Volt_Below_19','Max_Volt_19_Above']] = df[['Voltage','Min','Max','Median','Bounce_Back','Drop','Min_Volt_Below_19','Max_Volt_19_Above']].astype('float32')
    df[['Test_Record_Detail_Id']]= df[['Test_Record_Detail_Id']].astype('int32')
    df[['Rated','Measured']]= df[['Rated','Measured']].astype('int16')
    df[['Battery_Decision']] = df[['Battery_Decision']].astype('category')
    

    processed_data = remove_outliers(df)

    return processed_data

Map And Remove Function¶

In [ ]:
def map_and_remove(df):
    # Replace numerical classes 0,1,4,5,6 with correspoinding decision label 
    df['Battery_Decision'] = df['Battery_Decision'].map(bd_map)
    # Regroup categories into Good Battery and Bad Battery
    df.loc[:, 'Battery_Decision'] = df.loc[:, 'Battery_Decision'].apply(batterydecision)

    #Keep Only Class GOOD BATTERY  and Class BAD BATTERY
    df = df.query('(Battery_Decision == "GOOD BATTERY") | (Battery_Decision == "BAD BATTERY")')

    return df

#Return mapped and cleaned data
mvt1_clean = map_and_remove(mvt1_clean)
fgpc_clean = map_and_remove(fgpc_clean)

Based on the results of the Correlation Heatmap, one can see that certain features are very highly correlated such as Median and Average, Max and Max_Volt_19_Above, and Drop and Bounce_Back. Removeing one more of these features might help improve model preformance as highly correlated features can lead the model to overfit, especially if the two features aren't independned.

Drop & Train XGB Function¶

In [ ]:
#This function trains an xgboost classifer using either all features, or droping the specified columns. Then print validation and test performance scores\

def train_xgb(drop_columns: Union[List[str], None] = None): #Takes in list of column names to be dropped, or None

    if drop_columns is not None:   #If column(s) names are given, drop columns with matching name from X data, and train
        xgb = XGBClassifier(random_state = 42)
        xgb.fit(X_train.drop(columns=drop_columns),y_train,eval_set = [(X_val.drop(columns=drop_columns),y_val)], verbose = 0 )

        #Print Validation Results
        y_proba_xgb = xgb.predict_proba(X_val.drop(columns=drop_columns))
        y_predict_xgb = xgb.predict(X_val.drop(columns=drop_columns))
        print(f"--(Validation Set: Drop {drop_columns})--\nLog-Loss: {log_loss(y_val.drop(columns=drop_columns), y_proba_xgb)}\nTotal Accuracy:{accuracy_score(y_val.drop(columns=drop_columns), y_predict_xgb)}\n{classification_report(y_val, y_predict_xgb)}")
       
        # Print Test Results
        y_proba_xgb = xgb.predict_proba(X_test.drop(columns=drop_columns))
        y_predict_xgb = xgb.predict(X_test.drop(columns=drop_columns))
        print(f"--(Test Set: Drop {drop_columns})--\nLog-Loss: {log_loss(y_test.drop(columns=drop_columns), y_proba_xgb)}\nTotal Accuracy:{accuracy_score(y_test.drop(columns=drop_columns), y_predict_xgb)}\n{classification_report(y_test, y_predict_xgb)}")



    else:  #If no columns to drop are give, train model using all the features

        xgb = XGBClassifier(random_state = 42)
        xgb.fit(X_train,y_train,eval_set = [(X_val,y_val)],verbose = 0)
        
        #Print Validation Results
        y_proba_xgb_val = xgb.predict_proba(X_val)
        y_predict_xgb_val = xgb.predict(X_val)
        print(f"--(Validation Set: All Features)\nLog-Loss: {log_loss(y_val, y_proba_xgb_val)}\nTotal Accuracy:{accuracy_score(y_val, y_predict_xgb_val)}\n{classification_report(y_val, y_predict_xgb_val)}")
        
        # Print Test Results
        y_proba_xgb_test = xgb.predict_proba(X_test)
        y_predict_xgb_test = xgb.predict(X_test)
        print(f"--(Test Set: All Features)--\nLog-Loss: {log_loss(y_test, y_proba_xgb_test)}\nTotal Accuracy:{accuracy_score(y_test, y_predict_xgb_test)}\n{classification_report(y_test, y_predict_xgb_test)}")

        return y_proba_xgb_val, y_predict_xgb_val,

XGBoost Feature Selection Results¶

Train different generic XGBoost models, testing the effect of dropping different features. For example, since average and median are very highly correlated,so first we can test to see if dropping either average or median can improve model performance. Then we can check to see if dropping the Slope_Drop feature improves performance since it is the feature with the least importance.

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np

# Function to scale the values
def scale_values(values):
    min_val = min(values)
    scaled_values = [(val - min_val) / min_val * 100 for val in values]
    return scaled_values

# Create subplots for each metric
fig, ax = plt.subplots(3, 1, figsize=(15, 25))

metrics = ["log_loss", "accuracy", "f1_score"]
for i, metric in enumerate(metrics):
    validation_values = [value["validation"][metric] for value in data.values()]
    test_values = [value["test"][metric] for value in data.values()]
    
    # Scale the values
    validation_scaled = scale_values(validation_values)
    test_scaled = scale_values(test_values)
    
    # Create line plot with markers
    ax[i].plot(data.keys(), validation_scaled, marker='o', color="b", label="Validation")
    ax[i].plot(data.keys(), test_scaled, marker='o', color="r", label="Test")
    
    # Add data labels
    for j, key in enumerate(data.keys()):
        va_validation = "bottom" if validation_scaled[j] > np.mean(validation_scaled) else "top"
        va_test = "bottom" if test_scaled[j] > np.mean(test_scaled) else "top"
        ax[i].annotate(f"{validation_values[j]:.4f}", (key, validation_scaled[j]), textcoords="offset points", xytext=(0,10), ha='center', va=va_validation, fontsize=12, color="b")
        ax[i].annotate(f"{test_values[j]:.4f}", (key, test_scaled[j]), textcoords="offset points", xytext=(0,-15), ha='center', va=va_test, fontsize=12, color="r")
    
    ax[i].set_ylabel(f"{metric} (% difference from min)")
    ax[i].legend()

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()
In [ ]:
'''

Based on the results so far, we can see that dropping either the Average, Median, or Slope_Drop will increase model performance just slightly.
Although dropping any single one of those columns increases overall performance, the features that increases performance the most when dropped individually are Slop_Drop 
and Min_Volt_Below_19. Dropping Min_Volt_Below_19 yeilds a lower logloss but also lowers accuracy very slighly (neglegable?). 
We will now test to see if dropping a combination of two or more features can help improve the model. 

'''

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np

    "All Features": {

    },

The results above indicate that dropping all conductance related features ('Conductance', 'Rated', 'Voltage') decreases the performance of the model significantlly. Accuracy score decreases from 94% down to 87%. Log-loss increases from 0.1428 to 0.3202. This makes sense as Conductance and Voltage are among the top 5 most important features.

XGB Hyperparameter Optimization¶

In [ ]:
drop_columns = ['Conductance','Rated','Measured']

X_train = X_train.drop(columns = drop_columns)
X_val = X_val.drop(columns = drop_columns)
X_test = X_test.drop(columns = drop_columns)
In [ ]:
def objective(trial):
    # Define hyperparameters
    params = {
        'n_estimators': trial.suggest_int('n_estimators', 50, 500),
        'max_depth': trial.suggest_int('max_depth', 1, 10),
        'learning_rate': trial.suggest_float('learning_rate', 0.01, 1.0),
        'subsample': trial.suggest_float('subsample', 0.1, 1.0),
        'colsample_bytree': trial.suggest_float('colsample_bytree', 0.1, 1.0),
        'gamma': trial.suggest_float('gamma', 0.0, 1.0),
        'min_child_weight':trial.suggest_int('min_child_weight',1,20),
        'scale_pos_weight': trial.suggest_float('scale_pos_weight', 1e-6, 1e6, log=True)  # Handle class imbalance
    }

    model = XGBClassifier(**params, eval_metric='logloss',random_state = 42)
    model.fit(X_train,y_train,eval_set = [(X_val,y_val)], verbose = 0)

    y_proba = model.predict_proba(X_val)
    loss = log_loss(y_val, y_proba)

    # Report intermediate result
    trial.report(loss, step=0)

    # Handle pruning based on the intermediate result
    if trial.should_prune():
        raise optuna.TrialPruned()
    return loss

# Create a study with a pruner (MedianPruner)
study = optuna.create_study(direction='minimize', pruner=optuna.pruners.HyperbandPruner())

# Optimize the objective function with a given number of trials
study.optimize(objective,  n_trials=500,n_jobs=-1,show_progress_bar=True)

print('Best trial:')
trial = study.best_trial

print('  Value: ', trial.value)
print('  Params: ')
for key, value in trial.params.items():
    print('    {}: {}'.format(key, value))

Optimization with Optuna (TabNet)¶

XGB + Deep Learning Ensamble¶

In [ ]:
clf = TabNetClassifier(
    device_name='cuda',mask_type='entmax',
    n_a = 8,    # Number of attention 
    n_d = 8,
    seed = 42,
    verbose = 1,
    optimizer_params = {'lr': 0.01},
    optimizer_fn = torch.optim.Adam,
    scheduler_fn = torch.optim.lr_scheduler.CosineAnnealingLR,
    scheduler_params = {'T_max': 10, 'eta_min': 0},
    lambda_sparse = 0.01,
    n_steps = 2
)


clf.fit(
    
    X_train = X_train.values,y_train = y_train,
    eval_set=[(X_train.values,y_train),(X_val.values, y_val)],
    eval_metric=['logloss'],
    eval_name = ['train','validation'],
    max_epochs=400, patience=100,
    batch_size=8192, virtual_batch_size=256,
    num_workers=48,
    weights=1,
    )


clf.save_model("tabnet_classifier_beta2")

# Assuming clf is your trained TabNetClassifier model
history = clf.history

# Plotting losses
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 5))
plt.plot(history['loss'], label='Training Loss')
plt.plot(history['validation_logloss'], label='Validation Loss')
plt.plot(history['train_logloss'], label='Train Loss')

# Assuming you have test loss
# plt.plot(history['test_loss'], label='Test Loss')
plt.xlabel('Epochs')
plt.ylabel('Loss')
plt.title('Training, Validation and Test Loss over Epochs')
plt.legend()
plt.show()

# Plotting learning rate
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 5))
plt.plot(history['lr'])
plt.xlabel('Epochs')
plt.ylabel('Learning Rate')
plt.title('Learning Rate over Epochs')
plt.show()

Find best xgb meta learner¶

Here we use Optuna once again to optimize the hyper-parameters of an XGBoostClassifier. This time the classifier will serve as our 'Meta Learner', and will be trained on the predicted probabilites of the previous best XGB and best TabNet models. We then tell the Optuna api to perform a serach such that the best combination of hyperparameters is the combination that minimizes the log-loss on the test set, which in this case is being used as the 'validation' set. This ensure that our final meta learner has good generizablity.

In [ ]:
# Define the objective function for Optuna to optimize
def objective(trial):
    # Define the hyperparameter search space
    params = {
        "n_estimators": trial.suggest_int("n_estimators", 30, 400),
        "learning_rate": trial.suggest_float("learning_rate", 0.001, 1.0),
        "max_depth": trial.suggest_int("max_depth", 1, 5),
        "min_child_weight": trial.suggest_float("min_child_weight", 0.1, 10.0),
        "subsample": trial.suggest_float("subsample", 0.1, 1.0),
        "gamma": trial.suggest_float('gamma', 0.0, 1.0),
        "colsample_bytree": trial.suggest_float("colsample_bytree", 0.1, 1.0),
        "reg_alpha": trial.suggest_float("reg_alpha", 0.0, 10.0),
        "reg_lambda": trial.suggest_float("reg_lambda", 0.0, 10.0),
        "scale_pos_weight":  trial.suggest_float("scale_pos_weight",0,4)

    }

    # Create the XGBoost model with the suggested hyperparameters
    model = XGBClassifier(random_state=42, eval_metric='logloss',callbacks=[optuna.integration.XGBoostPruningCallback(trial, observation_key="validation_0-logloss")], **params)

    # Fit the model with hyperparameter tuning
    model.fit(X_val_with_probs, y_val, eval_set= [(X_test_with_probs,y_test)],verbose=0)

    # Evaluate the model
    y_proba = model.predict_proba(X_test_with_probs)
    loss = log_loss(y_test, y_proba)
     
    return loss


# Enable hyperband pruning with the number of trials set to 500
study = optuna.create_study(direction="minimize", pruner= HyperbandPruner(min_resource=50), study_name="xgb_hyperparameter_tuning")
study.optimize(objective, n_trials=2000, n_jobs=-1)
best_trial = study.best_trial

Meta Learner Validation¶

Combine dataset for final validation¶

In [ ]:
combined_data = pd.concat([X_train, X_val, X_test], ignore_index=True)
combined_labels = pd.concat([y_train,y_val,y_test],ignore_index=True)

Get probabilities¶

In [ ]:
tabnet_val_proba =  clf.predict_proba(combined_data.values)
tabnet_val_preds =  clf.predict(combined_data.values)
In [ ]:
xgb_val_proba = best_xgb.predict_proba(combined_data.values)
xgb_val_preds = best_xgb.predict(combined_data.values)
In [ ]:
# Convert probabilities to a DataFrame
prob_df = pd.DataFrame(tabnet_val_proba, columns=[f'prob_{i}' for i in range(tabnet_val_proba.shape[1])])
prob_xgb = pd.DataFrame(xgb_val_proba, columns=[f'prob_{i}' for i in range(xgb_val_proba.shape[1])])

# Reset indices of X_train (to ensure alignment when concatenating)
X_val_probs = X_val.reset_index(drop=True)

# Concatenate probabilities with original data
X_val_probs = pd.concat([prob_df,prob_xgb], axis=1).values

meta_proba = meta_model.predict_proba(X_val_probs)
meta_preds = meta_model.predict(X_val_probs)
